body:
BTW
I reported an earlier problem relating to the delays in the circuit not being respected.
That was fixed in master. https://github.com/steveicarus/iverilog/issues/193
But then I notice my other tests were failing.

I am on latest master 3f49dfcd9787fb184ee0b5562e15cf0fbc65a33e
I rewound two commits and reran the test and it passes (but theb 193 breaks of course).
So it looks like something in that latest commit or two caused the deviation.

I will stay on the earlier commit for now because I prefer the work around for the timing issue vs hacking the pulldown approach. 

----

The test below fails.
It used to pass on recent master, and still passes on eda playground version.
Demo of  that works on old verilog: https://www.edaplayground.com/x/kD7

Full code below.

It looks like the aproach I am using to pull down to 0 causes a conflict with the H outputs of my buffer which is not what I expect a pull down to do - am I misusing it?

It seems to work on old verilog so I'm reporting this as an issue - though perhaps I've been misusing it all along??

BTW  In addition to this below, I think there is still something weird going on with handling those timings. 
The test can also be made to pass if we comment out the specify block.
Even replacing the specify with inline timings on the 74245 assign works, just not the specify approach.


---

Summary - the code below fails on master (my copy is 2 weeks old) but passes on last release.
This code can be made to pass the test either by
- removing the Specify block (FIX1) , or 
- changing the pulldown aproach (FIX2). 


```
`timescale 1ns/100ps
`default_nettype none

module hct74245( 
    input dir,
    input nOE,
    inout [7:0] A,
    inout [7:0] B
);

      // FIX1 - remove this specify block (btw inline timings on the assign don't fail)
        specify
            (A => B) = (10);
            (B => A) = (10);
            (dir *> A) = (16);
            (dir *> B) = (16);
            (nOE *> A) = (16);
            (nOE *> B) = (16);
        endspecify

    assign A=nOE? 8'bzzzzzzzz :dir?8'bzzzzzzzz:B;
    assign B=nOE? 8'bzzzzzzzz :dir?A:8'bzzzzzzzz;

    always @(*)
        $display("%6d", $time,  " BUF : A=%8b ", A, "B=%-8b ", B, "dir=%1b", dir, " nOE=%1b", nOE);
   
endmodule: hct74245



// THE FIRST TEST FAILS ON MASTER

module test();

    wire AtoB=1'b1;     // direction A to B

    logic nOEvar=0;      // output enabled
    wire nOE=nOEvar;      // output enabled

    // I expect this same value on B !!!!!!
    wire [7:0] A = 8'b10101010;       

    // FIX2: Remove the pulldown and change this from tri to tri0 and then the test passes
    tri  [7:0] B;                                   
    
    // transceiver - B should either follow A or be pulled low 
    hct74245 bufTest(.A, .B, .dir(AtoB), .nOE); 

    // FIX2:  Remove this pulldown and change the B wire from tri to tri0 and then the test passes
    pulldown pullTo0[7:0](B);

    always @(*) 
        $display("%6d", $time,  " TEST: A=%8b ", A, "B=%-8b ", B);

    initial begin

        // output B should follow input A because nOE is low
        nOEvar=1'b0;      // output enabled
        #100
        if (B !== 8'b10101010) begin 
            $display("FAILED 1: '%b' is not '%b' ", B, 8'b10101010);
            $finish_and_return(1); 
        end

        // output B should be 0 because nOE is high, and B should be Z therefore pulldown should pull to 0
        nOEvar=1'b1;      // output disabled
        #100
        if (B !== 8'b00000000) begin 
            $display("FAILED 2: '%8b' is not '%8b' ", B, 8'b00000000);
            $finish_and_return(1); 
        end
    end
endmodule : test
```

